x4freetext: Berkeley 88-inch cyclotron
He-3++ beam.
Thin targets were irradiated simultaneously at
different energies by stacked-foil technique. Thick
targets were irradiated one-at-a-time with a thin
standard in the same stack, or with a thick standard
from two successive irradiations.
Two Ge(Li) detectors, having active volumes of
l6 cm3 and 30 cm3
Absolute cross-sections were calculated
based on the assumption that the reactions were
attributed entirely to a single reaction on a
specific target nuclide.
Each of the cross-sections shown in `data-section`
represents an average value of 2-3 replicates.
The estimated absolute uncertainty in the
cross sections includes:
* uncertainty in the determination of total
beam current,
* uncertainty in the half-lives of nuclides,
* uncertainty in the determination of disintegration
rates,
* the uniformity of thickness of targets,
* possibility of recoil gas losses during irradiation.
Average deviation.

aluminum over the sulfur to promote heat transfer
during the irradiations. The thickness of the targets
were determined by weighing; they ranged from 1.5 to
